Jessica A. Bolin

Bio

I am a PhD Candidate at USC Australia and CSIRO Oceans and Atmosphere, working on forecasting jellymeat (post-mortem myoliquefaction) in broadbill swordfish harvested off Eastern Australia. I am a Chapter Scientist and Contributing Author for the Oceans and Coastal Ecosystems and their Services chapter for Working Group Twos contribution to the IPCCs Sixth Assessment Report, and tutor ecological statistics in R at USC. Broadly, my research interests span seafood sustainability, food security, climate change, dynamic risk adaptation and planetary health.

Publications

Most recent:

  • Bolin J, Schoeman D, Evans K, Cummins S, Scales K. 2021, Achieving sustainable and climate-resilient fisheries requires marine ecosystem forecasts to include fish condition. Fish and Fisheries.
  • Bolin J, Cummins S, Mitu S, Schoeman D, Evans K, Scales K. 2021, First report of Kudoa thunni and Kudoa musculoliquefaciens affecting the quality of commercially harvested yellowfin tuna and broadbill swordfish in Eastern Australia. Parasitology Research.

A full list of my publications can be found on my Google Scholar page. Im also keen and available to serve as a reviewer. So far, I have reviewed for Scientific Reports, Marine Biology, Fisheries Research, Marine Environmental Research and Parasitology Research.

Recorded Talks

You can find all of my recorded talks on my Vimeo page. Recent talks are linked below:

  • Forecasting swordfish quality in a climate-change hotspot: a tool for dynamic industry adaptation, World Fisheries Congress (2021)
  • Advancing marine ecosystem forecasting for efficient, sustainable and climate-resilient fisheries, Australian Marine Science Association Conference (2021)
  • Are you ready for this jelly?, Three-Minute Thesis Asia-Pacific Grand Final (2020)
